<TITLE> WB commits $250m for power </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, February 24 (bdnews24.com)  The World Bank has committed $250 million in financial assistance to develop the power sector, the ministry said in a press release Tuesday. The government has a specific commitment to develop the power sector, the prime minister's adviser Toufique-e-Elahi Chowdhury said in a meeting with World Bank country director Xian Zhu. "That's why the government is willing to diversify energy to produce power. We are considering every source of energy, gas, coal, oil and renewables," the statement quotes Chowdhury as saying. The adviser also asked for World Bank assistance to install new power plants and rehabilitate the old. Xian Zhu assured all types of support for development of the power sector, said the statement. "WB will work to involve the private sector to install new power plant" it quoted Zhu as saying. The Bank pledged $150 million to help establish the Southern Power Distribution Company and $100 million in financial assistance for the Rural Electrification Board. WB is supporting the government initiative to increase rural people's access to electricity through the Rural Electrification and Renewable Energy Development (RERED) Project. Under this project, more than 520,000 consumers in rural areas have received electricity connections since Jan 2003. The REB has so far constructed and renovated about 19,500km of power lines. bdn
